# Push and pull request workflow

Applies whenever you complete **substantive** work on a **task branch** (not `dev` / `main`), unless the user explicitly asked for local-only or no-PR delivery.

See `.cursor/rules/git-dev-integration-branch.mdc` — feature PRs **always** target **`dev`**, not `main`.

## Required steps

1. **Inspect git:** Run `git status` and `git log origin/$(git branch --show-current)..HEAD 2>/dev/null || git log @{u}..HEAD 2>/dev/null` (or equivalent) to see if there are **commits** not yet on the remote.
2. **Push:** If the branch is ahead of its upstream (or has no upstream and has local commits), run `git push -u origin HEAD` (first time) or `git push`. Resolve auth errors; do not force-push to shared branches except when the user explicitly requests a safe force (e.g. lease).
3. **Open a PR:** If no PR exists for this branch, run `gh pr create --base dev` with a clear title and body. Include the Linear id (e.g. **DEV-387**) and link when the work maps to Linear. Prefer `gh pr view` / `gh pr list --head $(git branch --show-current)` to avoid duplicates.
4. **If `gh` is missing or fails:** Paste the exact `git push` and GitHub “compare & PR” URL instructions so the user can finish in one step.

## When there is nothing to push

If changes are only in the working tree and **there are no commits yet**, do not claim the work is “opened as a PR.” Remind the user that **commits must exist** before push/PR; this repo’s convention is that **the user commits** unless they told you otherwise for that task.

## Exceptions

- Trivial typo-only edits when the user asked not to open a PR.
- The user is on `main` with instructions not to branch (rare; follow their instruction).
